---
import PageShell from '../../components/PageShell.astro';
import CTABox from '../../components/CTABox.astro';
import ComparisonTable from '../../components/ComparisonTable.astro';

const tocItems = [
  { id: 'top-picks', text: 'Our Top Picks', level: 2 },
  { id: 'leaving-netherlands', text: 'Leaving Dutch Insurance', level: 2 },
  { id: 'svb-option', text: 'SVB Voluntary Insurance', level: 2 },
  { id: 'comparison-table', text: 'Quick Comparison', level: 2 },
  { id: 'detailed-reviews', text: 'Detailed Reviews', level: 2 },
  { id: 'returning-to-netherlands', text: 'Returning to NL', level: 2 },
  { id: 'faqs', text: 'Common Questions', level: 2 },
];

const relatedLinks = [
  { title: 'Cigna Global Review', href: '/providers/cigna-global' },
  { title: 'Allianz Care Review', href: '/providers/allianz-care' },
  { title: 'Netherlands DAFT Visa Insurance', href: '/compare/best-insurance-for-netherlands-daft-visa' },
  { title: 'Best Europe Insurance', href: '/best/europe-insurance' },
  { title: 'Best German Expat Insurance', href: '/best/german-expat-insurance' },
];

const comparisonColumns = [
  { key: 'provider', header: 'Provider' },
  { key: 'dutchSupport', header: 'Dutch Support' },
  { key: 'euCoverage', header: 'EU Coverage' },
  { key: 'nlVisits', header: 'NL Coverage' },
  { key: 'price', header: 'Starting Price' },
];

const comparisonRows = [
  { provider: 'Cigna Global', dutchSupport: 'Limited', euCoverage: 'Full', nlVisits: 'Add-on', price: '€180/mo' },
  { provider: 'Allianz Care', dutchSupport: 'Yes', euCoverage: 'Full', nlVisits: 'Add-on', price: '€200/mo' },
  { provider: 'Bupa Global', dutchSupport: 'Limited', euCoverage: 'Full', nlVisits: 'Included', price: '€220/mo' },
  { provider: 'OOM Verzekeringen', dutchSupport: 'Full (Dutch)', euCoverage: 'Full', nlVisits: 'Included', price: '€150/mo' },
  { provider: 'Aon Netherlands', dutchSupport: 'Full (Dutch)', euCoverage: 'Full', nlVisits: 'Included', price: '€170/mo' },
];
---

<PageShell
  title="Best Health Insurance for Dutch Expats 2026"
  description="Compare international health insurance for Dutch expats. Understand your options when leaving the mandatory Dutch insurance system and how to protect your return rights."
  headline="Best Insurance for Dutch Expats in 2026"
  subheadline="Leaving the Netherlands means leaving mandatory health insurance behind. Here's how to stay covered abroad while keeping your options open for returning."
  heroBackgroundImage="/images/pages/dutch-expat-hero-bg.png"
  tocItems={tocItems}
  relatedLinks={relatedLinks}
  ctaButtonText="Get Cigna Quote →"
  ctaButtonHref="/go/cigna-global"
>
  <h2 id="top-picks">Our Top Picks</h2>
  <p>
    Dutch expats face a unique situation: the Netherlands has mandatory health insurance, so leaving requires formal deregistration. Here's what we recommend for coverage abroad:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Cigna Global:</strong> Best overall for Dutch expats. Comprehensive global coverage with strong EU networks. Reliable claims processing and 24/7 support.</li>
    <li><strong>OOM Verzekeringen:</strong> Dutch specialist in expat insurance. Full Dutch-language service, designed specifically for Nederlanders abroad.</li>
    <li><strong>Allianz Care:</strong> Strong European coverage with good Dutch support. Competitive pricing for EU destinations.</li>
    <li><strong>Aon Netherlands:</strong> Dutch broker offering international solutions. Good for complex situations or corporate expats.</li>
    <li><strong>Bupa Global:</strong> Premium option with excellent worldwide coverage, especially good for outside the EU.</li>
  </ul>

  <CTABox
    title="Mandatory Insurance Alert"
    description="When you return to the Netherlands, you must arrange health insurance within 4 months. There's no gap allowed—international insurance won't satisfy the Dutch requirement for basisverzekering."
    buttonText="Compare Options"
    buttonHref="/go/cigna-global"
    variant="highlight"
  />

  <h2 id="leaving-netherlands">Leaving Dutch Insurance</h2>
  <p>
    The Netherlands has a unique mandatory health insurance system (zorgverzekering). When you leave, several things happen:
  </p>

  <h3>Deregistering (Uitschrijven)</h3>
  <p>
    When you leave the Netherlands for longer than 8 months, you must deregister at your gemeente. This triggers several automatic processes:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>Your basisverzekering ends (you'll need to notify your insurer)</li>
    <li>Your aanvullende verzekering ends</li>
    <li>Your zorgtoeslag (healthcare allowance) stops</li>
    <li>Your BSN remains active for 20 years but becomes inactive for healthcare</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Cancelling Your Dutch Insurance</h3>
  <p>
    Contact your zorgverzekeraar (CZ, VGZ, Zilveren Kruis, etc.) to cancel your policy. They'll require proof of deregistration or proof of insurance abroad. Don't cancel before you have international coverage in place—there should be no gap.
  </p>

  <h3>Eigen Risico Refund</h3>
  <p>
    If you've paid your eigen risico (deductible) for the year, you may be entitled to a partial refund for unused months. Check with your insurer.
  </p>

  <div class="bg-amber-50 border border-amber-200 rounded-lg p-6 my-6">
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-amber-900 mb-2">Staying in the EU?</h3>
    <p class="text-amber-800">
      If you're moving to another EU country, EU coordination rules apply. You may be insured under the other country's system, or you may need international insurance depending on your employment status. It's complex—consider consulting a verzekeringadviseur.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h2 id="svb-option">SVB Voluntary Insurance</h2>
  <p>
    The SVB (Sociale Verzekeringsbank) offers voluntary insurance for Dutch people living abroad. This covers AOW pension accumulation and can include some healthcare elements.
  </p>

  <h3>What SVB Covers</h3>
  <p>
    SVB voluntary insurance primarily covers:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>AOW (state pension) accumulation</li>
    <li>ANW (survivor benefits)</li>
    <li>WLZ (long-term care—in some cases)</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>What SVB Doesn't Cover</h3>
  <p>
    SVB is NOT a substitute for health insurance. You still need separate international health coverage for:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Doctor visits and hospital care</li>
    <li>Prescriptions</li>
    <li>Emergency treatment</li>
    <li>Routine healthcare abroad</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Consider SVB voluntary insurance if you're concerned about maintaining your AOW entitlement. It's separate from health insurance decisions.
  </p>

  <h2 id="comparison-table">Quick Comparison</h2>
  <ComparisonTable columns={comparisonColumns} rows={comparisonRows} />

  <h2 id="detailed-reviews">Detailed Reviews</h2>

  <h3>Cigna Global</h3>
  <p>
    Cigna Global is our top recommendation for Dutch expats seeking comprehensive international coverage. Their Global Health Plan offers three tiers with coverage from €1 million to unlimited. Strong networks across Europe, Asia, and the Americas make it suitable for most Dutch expat destinations.
  </p>

  <p>
    Claims processing is efficient—typically 48-72 hours for straightforward claims. Direct billing is available at major hospitals worldwide. Netherlands coverage can be added for visits home.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Best for:</strong> Dutch expats who want reliable global coverage with strong service standards.
  </p>

  <h3>OOM Verzekeringen</h3>
  <p>
    OOM specializes in insurance for Dutch people abroad. Everything is in Dutch, staff understand Dutch healthcare expectations, and plans are designed for the specific needs of Nederlanders living overseas.
  </p>

  <p>
    Their Expat Health Insurance includes coverage in the Netherlands, so you're covered during visits home without needing add-ons. Plans offer various levels from basic to comprehensive.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Best for:</strong> Dutch expats who prefer dealing entirely in Dutch with a specialist provider.
  </p>

  <h3>Allianz Care</h3>
  <p>
    Allianz Care offers strong European coverage at competitive prices. Good option for Dutch expats staying within Europe. Plans range from Essential to Platinum with comprehensive benefits including mental health and maternity.
  </p>

  <p>
    Dutch-language support is available, and the Allianz brand is well-recognized throughout Europe. Direct billing works at most major European hospitals.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Best for:</strong> Dutch expats in Europe who want comprehensive coverage at reasonable prices.
  </p>

  <h3>Aon Netherlands</h3>
  <p>
    Aon Netherlands offers international health insurance solutions through their Dutch office. They're particularly good for corporate expats or complex situations requiring customized coverage.
  </p>

  <p>
    As a broker, Aon can arrange coverage from multiple underwriters, finding the best fit for your situation. Service is in Dutch, and they understand Dutch tax and social security implications.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Best for:</strong> Corporate expats or those with complex insurance needs requiring expert guidance.
  </p>

  <CTABox
    title="Get Multiple Quotes"
    description="Pricing varies significantly based on age, destination, and coverage level. Compare quotes from Dutch specialists and international insurers."
    buttonText="Compare Plans"
    buttonHref="/go/cigna-global"
  />

  <h2 id="returning-to-netherlands">Returning to the Netherlands</h2>
  <p>
    Returning to the Netherlands triggers mandatory health insurance requirements. Here's what to expect:
  </p>

  <h3>4-Month Rule</h3>
  <p>
    From the date you register at a Dutch gemeente, you have 4 months to arrange basisverzekering. Your coverage will be backdated to your registration date, so you're covered from day one—but you must arrange it within the timeframe.
  </p>

  <h3>Acceptatieplicht</h3>
  <p>
    Dutch insurers have acceptatieplicht (obligation to accept) for basisverzekering. They cannot reject you based on health conditions for basic coverage. Aanvullende verzekering (supplementary coverage) may have underwriting requirements.
  </p>

  <h3>Zorgtoeslag</h3>
  <p>
    Once you have Dutch insurance, you can apply for zorgtoeslag if your income qualifies. The benefit is paid monthly to help cover premiums.
  </p>

  <h3>Transition Period</h3>
  <p>
    Keep your international insurance active until your Dutch coverage begins. Many expats maintain international coverage for the first month after return while sorting out registration and Dutch insurance applications.
  </p>

  <h2 id="faqs">Common Questions</h2>

  <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">Can I keep my Dutch insurance abroad?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">No. Dutch basisverzekering is for residents only. When you deregister, your insurance must end. Some insurers offer international products as alternatives.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">What about short trips abroad?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">For trips under 8 months, you remain Dutch-insured. Your EHIC covers emergencies in the EU. Consider travel insurance for non-EU trips or additional coverage.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">Does international insurance count for return?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">No. When you return to NL, you must get Dutch basisverzekering. International insurance doesn't satisfy the mandatory insurance requirement.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">What about my AOW?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">You lose 2% of AOW for each year abroad without voluntary SVB insurance. Consider voluntary contributions if maximizing pension matters to you.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">Can I be refused Dutch insurance on return?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">No. Acceptatieplicht means all Dutch insurers must accept you for basisverzekering regardless of health conditions. Aanvullende verzekering may have restrictions.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-white p-6 rounded-lg border border-neutral-200">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-lg mb-2">Is OOM or Cigna better?</h3>
      <p class="text-neutral-600">OOM offers full Dutch service and specializes in Dutch expats. Cigna offers broader international networks and service in multiple languages. Choose based on your priorities.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2>Final Verdict</h2>
  <p>
    Dutch expats have excellent options for international health insurance. <strong>Cigna Global</strong> is our top recommendation for comprehensive coverage with strong global networks. <strong>OOM Verzekeringen</strong> is ideal for those who prefer a fully Dutch experience from a specialist provider.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Allianz Care</strong> offers good value for EU-based expats, while <strong>Aon Netherlands</strong> provides expert guidance for complex situations.
  </p>

  <p>
    Before leaving, notify your zorgverzekeraar and ensure there's no gap between your Dutch coverage ending and international coverage starting. And remember: returning to the Netherlands triggers mandatory insurance requirements within 4 months of registration.
  </p>

</PageShell>
